Impacts of MSA Policy Changes on Fisheries & Livelihood

Question 1: How was fish stock, GDP, and commercial fishing employment impacted by the two policy changes?

Q1 PART 1: Regional Scale - Is there a pattern across the region?

Looking at the region as a whole, it is difficult to see a clear pattern of the impact that the MSA amendments had on the region. This is likely because the MSA is just one government intervention and the seas are impacted by many forces that come from many directions – country policy, international dynamics, climate change etc.

Fish Stock & Haul

In terms of fish stocks, many species seemed to rebound following the 2007 Amendment – likely due to updated regulations on bycatch and using driftnets. However, the populations of many of the same species seem to plumet only a few years later. Overall, fish stocks seem to fluctuate independent of the policy amendments. The same goes for the amount of fish caught.

Data on fish stock from 2005 to 2022 was downloaded from NOAA StockSMART. Data on all stocks was downloaded for the two marine ecosystems which are relevant to the region of study: Atlantic Highly Migratory (AHM) and Northeast Shelf (NES).

Regional GDP & Fishing Industry Employment

There seems to be a stronger correlation between the MSA Amendments and impact on regional employment. In particular, after the 2018 Amendment, there was a steep increase across several states. This is likely due to improved clarity for regulations that govern fisheries that operate as commercial and recreational businesses. Such changes might have encouraged more businesses to convert to this mixed model – consequently diversifying against external shocks.

Data on GDP and employment from 2005 to 2022 was downloaded from .

Q1 PART 2: State Scale - Are there region-specific patterns?

From the three maps below, it is clear that just a few counties have high fisheries employment but that there is little overlap between counties with high employment and counties that have high GDP per capita – across the three time periods. Bristol County – seen in the dark orange on the Employment Map has the highest employment across the three time periods. Overtime, most other counties lose employment in the fisheries sector.

For fish haul, we were unable to find county-scale data but it is still interesting to see how Maine and Massachusetts dominate the fisheries industry. Use the horizontal scroll bar and drop down to investigate the change before and after the two MSA amendments.
